<!--
  Vault VM: Wazuh agent <localfile> for the ModSecurity event stream.

  Append this inside any <ossec_config> block in the Vault VM's
  /var/ossec/etc/ossec.conf, then restart the agent:
      sudo systemctl restart wazuh-agent
      sudo grep modsec-events /var/ossec/logs/ossec.log | tail
      # expect: Analyzing file: '/var/log/modsec-events/events.log'

  Multiple <ossec_config> blocks at the top level are valid Wazuh
  syntax; the agent merges them at load time. Easiest pattern is to
  drop a new <ossec_config> below the stock ones rather than splice
  into existing blocks.

  Single source: /var/log/modsec-events/events.log

  Flat JSON, one line per ModSecurity audit transaction, emitted by the
  sidecar at sidecar/modsec-tail.py. Fields: event_type / ts / srcip /
  method / path / http_code / engine / rule_ids / n_rules /
  anomaly_score / band / unique_id / hostname.

  IMPORTANT: this tails the sidecar's OUTPUT, not
  /srv/bw-logs/modsec_audit.log directly. The raw audit log is JSON
  too, but Wazuh's JSON decoder collapses its messages[] array into one
  opaque string, so the matched rule IDs / severities / anomaly score
  are not individually filterable. The sidecar flattens them into clean
  scalar fields first. See manager-modsec-rules.xml for the full
  rationale.

  log_format=json tells the agent to ship raw JSON lines; the manager's
  built-in JSON decoder auto-extracts every key into data.* fields, so
  manager-modsec-rules.xml just filters by field=value without a custom
  decoder.

  Rotation of this file is handled by /etc/logrotate.d/modsec-events
  (host-side config, not in the repo; canonical text in
  Vaultwarden/README.md § Log Rotation). copytruncate so both the
  sidecar's append handle and the agent's read handle stay valid.
-->

<ossec_config>

  <localfile>
    <log_format>json</log_format>
    <location>/var/log/modsec-events/events.log</location>
  </localfile>

</ossec_config>
